**Q2 — Optimization**

*Why is cross-entropy loss preferred over MSE? Walk through the log-likelihood derivation and explain what happens to the loss landscape with MSE — specifically around vanishing gradients and non-convexity.*

Taking the negative log-likelihood of a Bernoulli distribution gives −[y log p + (1−y) log(1−p)], which is cross-entropy. The gradient with respect to w is simply (p−y)x because the sigmoid's derivative cancels cleanly with the log derivative. With MSE, the gradient becomes (p−y) · σ(z)(1−σ(z)) · x. Since σ′ ≈ 0 for large |z|, gradients vanish when the model is confidently wrong — the worst possible time to stop learning. Additionally, MSE + sigmoid creates a non-convex loss surface with local minima, while cross-entropy + sigmoid is strictly convex, guaranteeing a unique global minimum reachable by gradient descent.

