**Q4 — Regularization**

*Explain L1 vs L2 regularization — not just 'L1 gives sparsity' but why geometrically and probabilistically. With 10M features and ~1K relevant ones, which do you use and how do you set λ in production?*

Geometrically, the L2 penalty is a sphere and L1 is a diamond. The loss contour intersects the L1 diamond at its corners, which lie on the coordinate axes — this forces coefficients to exactly zero, producing sparsity structurally. The L2 contour is smooth with no corners, so it only shrinks coefficients, never zeroing them. Probabilistically, L2 corresponds to a Gaussian prior on weights; L1 corresponds to a Laplace prior, which has heavier tails and more mass at zero. With 10M features and 1K relevant ones, you need L1 (or elastic net) — L2 cannot perform implicit feature selection. For λ, search a log-spaced grid using cross-validated log-loss on a time-stratified validation set to avoid leakage, and monitor coefficient stability across retraining cycles.

