**Q5 — Imbalanced Data**

*Fraud detection: 0.1% positive rate, 99.9% accuracy. Walk through everything wrong with this and give three distinct technical strategies to fix it.*

The model has learned nothing — predicting "not fraud" always achieves 99.9% accuracy. Accuracy is the wrong metric entirely. Use AUC-PR (precision-recall curve), F1, or a business-cost-weighted metric where false negatives (missed fraud) cost far more than false positives. Three strategies: (1) Class-weight adjustment — set class weights inversely proportional to frequency (e.g. 1:1000), which rescales gradient contributions from minority samples, equivalent to oversampling without data duplication; (2) Threshold tuning — shift the decision threshold below 0.5 to increase recall at the cost of precision, calibrated to the business SLA; (3) Oversampling with SMOTE — synthesizes minority samples by interpolating in feature space rather than duplicating, giving the model richer signal. Important: after any resampling, recalibrate the output probabilities since the synthetic base rate no longer matches reality.

