**Q6 — System Design**

*Deploy LR at 500K predictions/second, p99 < 5ms, 50K sparse one-hot features. Full production architecture and LR-specific optimizations.*

LR's prediction is σ(w·x) — just a dot product. With 50K features but only ~100 non-zero entries per request, the effective compute is O(100), not O(50K) — exploit this with sparse weight lookup rather than dense matrix multiply. Architecture: features computed from a low-latency feature store (Redis or in-memory), model weights stored in a hash table (50K × 4 bytes = 200KB, fits entirely in L2 cache), inference served in C++ or Go for sub-millisecond execution. LR-specific optimizations: no backprop graph at inference, so zero framework overhead; weights can be quantized to int8 without meaningful quality loss since LR is robust to precision; feature hashing reduces storage further; batch sparse lookups to reduce cache misses. Compared to a neural net, LR needs no GPU, no matrix multiplication libraries, and has 10–100x lower memory — it wins decisively on latency and cost at this scale.

